  "text": "Cores were allowed to stabilize for 14 d, after which the experiment was initiated. This point is hereafter referred to as t = 0. Enriched cores received weekly pulses of labile OM in the form of commercial fish feed (Ecolife, Dansk Ørredfoder; C and N content of 49.4 and 1.22%, respectively). The enrichment procedure was identical to that of [CITATION_1] with respect to OM quality, quantity, and pulse frequency. Homogenized fish feed (0.29 g) was thoroughly mixed into 10 g of homogenized Fe-poor or Fe-rich sediment corresponding to a 1 mm thick layer of sediment after application. The enriched sediment pellet was applied directly to the surface of the cores with a spatula after removing the water phase. Cores were gently refilled with water, avoiding resuspension, and returned to the incubation tanks. The enrichment procedure was performed once a week throughout the experiment, and average organic C (OC) and N (ON) loading from the first enrichment to the end of the experiment was 357 and 50.3 mmol m -2 d -1 in Fe-poor cores, and 329 and 46.5 mmol m -2 d -1 in Fe-rich cores, respectively. Thus, the simulated organic loading rates were comparable to the range of sedimentation rates reported from beneath fish farms or mussel rafts (e.g. [CITATION_2] ) were determined on 3 enriched cores and 3 control cores twice a week. The frequency of flux measurements in control cores was reduced to once a week after 20 d. Initial water samples were taken from each core, which were subsequently closed with rubber stoppers. Enriched cores were incubated for 2 h and control cores for 5 h before the rubber stoppers were removed and final water samples were taken. Samples were preserved, stored, and analyzed according to the procedures described below. Changes in O 2 concentration during incubations were detected by an Ox100 mini electrode (Unisense).",
